<DOC><DOCNO> AP900803-0205 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-03-90 1432EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-03 0338</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0357</SECOND><BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Middle East oil worries and mounting recessionfears sent waves of selling through the stock market today, drivingthe Dow Jones industrial average more than 100 points.   Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips plunged 123.51 points to2,741.09 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street. The last time the average took abigger drop came in the ``mini-crash'' of last Oct. 13, when itfell 190.58 points.   Losers swamped gainers by about 7 to 1 among New York StockExchange-listed issues, with 219 up, 1,417 down and 311 unchanged.   Selling also battered the over-the-counter market, wheretechnology stocks showed steep losses.   The Labor Department reported this morning that nonfarm payrollemployment fell by 219,000 in July, surprising analysts who hadbeen looking for a modest increase.   The civilian unemployment rate jumped three-tenths of apercentage point, o 5.5 percent.   Those figures reinforced concern in the financial world thateconomic activity was weakening more than had been thought just afew weeks ago.   Many observers fear the economy's problems could be compoundedby a jump in oil prices arising from Iraq's invasion of Kuwait thisweek.   Selling intensified today as reports reached Wall Street thatIraqi forces were near the border of Saudi Arabia.   Among actively traded blue chips, International BusinessMachines dropped 4\ to 105{; Philip Morris 2\ to 44andrsqb;; Boeing 1} to51}; General Electric 3| to 67, and Bristol-Myers Squibb 2} to 59{.   In the energy sector, by contrast, Exxon gained 1} to 55; Texaco~ to 66} and Mobil 1 to 68\ as oil prices kept climbing.   In the over-the-counter market, Apple Computer fell 3 to 40{;MCI Communications 2andrsqb; to 34andrsqb;, and Intel 2} to 37{.   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell6.67 to 185.69. At the American Stock Exchange, the market valueindex was down 7.54 at 344.61.   Volume on the Big Board came to 207.34 million shares with twohours to go.</TEXT></DOC>